---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-thailand', text: 'Leaving Thai Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'language-support', text: 'Thai Language Support', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Thailand LTR Visa Insurance', href: '/compare/best-insurance-for-thailand-ltr-visa' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'thaiSupport', header: 'Thai Support' },
  { key: 'globalNetwork', header: 'Global Network' },
  { key: 'thailandCoverage', header: 'Thailand Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', thaiSupport: 'Yes', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', thailandCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', thaiSupport: 'Yes', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', thailandCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Pacific Cross Thailand', thaiSupport: 'Full (Thai)', globalNetwork: 'Good', thailandCoverage: 'Included', price: '$150/mo' },
  { provider: 'AIA Thailand', thaiSupport: 'Full (Thai)', globalNetwork: 'Limited', thailandCoverage: 'Included', price: '$140/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', thaiSupport: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Strong', thailandCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$175/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Thai Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Thai expats. Find coverage for the US, UK, Singapore, and other destinations with Thai language support options."
  headline="Best Insurance for Thai Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Thai citizens abroad need proper healthcare coverage. Here's how to stay protected while maintaining your options for returning home."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/thai-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Thai expats are found in significant numbers in the US, UK, Germany, Singapore, and other countries. Your insurance needs depend on destination and how you want to maintain coverage for Thailand visits. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Thai expats. Strong global networks, Thai-language support available, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. High-quality service throughout.</li>
    <li><strong>Pacific Cross Thailand:</strong> Thailand-based with international coverage. Full Thai service, includes Thailand coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>AIA Thailand:</strong> Major Thai insurer with some international options. Familiar brand, Thai service.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage with strong European networks.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Thai Language Support"
    description="Navigating healthcare in a foreign country is challenging. Prioritize insurers with Thai-speaking support lines for peace of mind during stressful situations."
    buttonText="Compare Thai-Supported Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-thailand">Leaving Thai Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Thailand has multiple healthcare schemes. Your situation depends on which system covers you:
  </p>

  <h3>Social Security (ประกันสังคม)</h3>
  <p>
    If you're employed in Thailand's formal sector, Social Security provides healthcare coverage. When you leave Thai employment and move abroad, this coverage ends. There's no mechanism to continue Social Security healthcare internationally.
  </p>

  <h3>Universal Coverage Scheme (30 Baht Scheme)</h3>
  <p>
    The Universal Coverage Scheme covers Thai citizens not in Social Security. It's tied to residence in Thailand—it doesn't provide international coverage and access requires being in Thailand.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Thai Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Thai private insurers (AIA, Muang Thai, Bangkok Insurance) offer some international coverage, typically limited to 30-90 days of emergency treatment. For long-term stays abroad, you need dedicated international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Government Officials (ข้าราชการ)</h3>
  <p>
    Government employees and retirees have separate healthcare benefits. Check with your department about international coverage options—some provide limited overseas coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="language-support">Thai Language Support</h2>
  <p>
    Access to Thai-language support can be crucial during medical emergencies:
  </p>

  <h3>What to Look For</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>24/7 Thai-speaking emergency hotline</li>
    <li>Claims processing support in Thai</li>
    <li>Thai-language documentation if needed</li>
    <li>Assistance finding Thai-speaking doctors abroad</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Provider Availability</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna and Bupa offer Thai support through their Asian operations. Thai insurers (Pacific Cross Thailand, AIA) provide full Thai service. Some international insurers have limited Thai capabilities—confirm before purchasing.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Finding Thai Doctors Abroad</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Major cities with Thai communities (Los Angeles, London, Singapore) often have Thai-speaking doctors. Your insurer can help locate providers, or check local Thai community networks.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage with Thai-language support through their Asia Pacific operations. Strong networks worldwide, including major Thai expat destinations. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    Thailand coverage can be added for visits home. Direct billing available at major hospitals worldwide.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Thai expats who want reliable global coverage with Thai support.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent networks worldwide. Thai support is available through their Thailand operations. Service quality is high throughout.
  </p>

  <p>
    Comprehensive benefits including mental health and maternity. Thailand coverage available as an add-on.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Thai expats who want premium coverage with top-tier service.
  </p>

  <h3>Pacific Cross Thailand</h3>
  <p>
    Pacific Cross Thailand is an established health insurer offering international products for Thai citizens abroad. Full Thai-language service, familiar processes, and Thailand coverage included automatically.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are adequate, strongest in Asia and popular Thai expat destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Thai expats who prefer Thai-language service and seamless Thailand coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>AIA Thailand</h3>
  <p>
    AIA is Thailand's largest life insurer and offers some health insurance products. Full Thai service, familiar brand, but international coverage options are more limited than dedicated international insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    Good for maintaining Thailand coverage; may need supplementing for extensive international needs.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Thai expats who want familiar Thai service and primarily need Thailand coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Balance global network strength against Thai-language support based on your comfort level and destination."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Thai expats should consider:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    US healthcare is extremely expensive—comprehensive coverage is essential. Los Angeles, New York, and Chicago have Thai communities with Thai-speaking doctors. Prioritize insurers with strong US networks and direct billing.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    NHS provides free healthcare to legal residents with proper visa status. Many Thai expats supplement NHS with private insurance for faster access. London has Thai medical professionals.
  </p>

  <h3>Singapore</h3>
  <p>
    Excellent healthcare but expensive. Work pass holders typically have employer-provided coverage. Private insurance ensures access to the best facilities. Singapore has many Thai-speaking healthcare providers.
  </p>

  <h3>Germany</h3>
  <p>
    Germany requires health insurance for all residents. Employment enrolls you in the German system. Significant Thai community in Germany, particularly in major cities.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does Thai Social Security cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. Thai Social Security only covers care in Thailand. You need dedicated international health insurance for coverage abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I use the 30 Baht scheme abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. The Universal Coverage Scheme only works in Thailand. International insurance is required for coverage while living abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Thai-language support important?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">It depends on your English comfort level. In medical emergencies, native language support reduces stress and misunderstandings. Consider your situation.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during Thailand visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most international insurers offer Thailand as a coverage region. Thai insurers include it automatically. Confirm details with your chosen provider.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Pacific Cross or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Pacific Cross offers full Thai service and includes Thailand. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on destination and language preference.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Thai doctors in the US?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes, especially in cities with large Thai communities like Los Angeles. Your insurer can help locate Thai-speaking providers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Thai expats need comprehensive international insurance—Thai public schemes don't provide international coverage. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for reliable coverage with Thai support. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those wanting the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pacific Cross Thailand</strong> suits those who prefer full Thai-language service and included Thailand coverage. <strong>AIA Thailand</strong> may work for those primarily focused on Thailand coverage with limited international needs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider your destination's healthcare costs and your language comfort level when choosing. US coverage especially requires strong networks due to high costs.
  </p>

</PageShell>
